battleSim: A Python implementation of a 538 Matlab script (DRAFT)¶

The webiste FiveThirtyEight set one of its weekly challenges as such:

Forget the Battle of Winterfell and model our battle as follows. Each army lines up single file, facing the other army. One soldier steps forward from each line and the pair duels — half the time the living soldier wins, half the time the dead soldier wins. If the living soldier wins, he goes to the back of his army’s line, and the dead soldier is out (the living army uses dragonglass weapons, so the dead soldier is dead forever this time). If the dead soldier wins, he goes to the back of their army’s line, but this time the (formerly) living soldier joins him there. (Reanimation is instantaneous for this Night King.) The battle continues until one army is entirely eliminated.

What starting sizes of the armies, living and dead, give each army a 50-50 chance of winning?

I made my solution as a matlab script to be run on a lab computer at Carleton University, since my machine did not have enough power to compute the results in a timely manner when using higher values for the variables.

Here I will try to rewrite it as a python script that might also not run very fast, but I will also use this as a platform to explain the process.

First, we create an array to store the values of each run. This will be a 2D array since we are testing against 2 variables, the number of soldiers in the Fallen army and the number of soldiers in the Living army.

In [1]:
count = 1000
results = [[0 for x in range(count)] for y in range(count)]

We then need to define a function that runs the simulation. We msut keep in mind the parameters of the riddle. In 50% of the battles (one on one), the Fallen soldier will win, which means that the Living army loses one soldier and at the same time, the Fallen army gains one soldier. The other 50% of the time, the Living soldier wins, which means that the Fallen army loses a soldier while the number of soldiers in the Living army stays the same.

In [2]:
def battleSim(fallen, living):
    
    if fallen < 1:
        return 1.0
    else:
        if living < 1:
            return 0.0
        else:
            if fallen < len(results) and living < len(results[0]) and results[fallen][living] > 0:
                return results[fallen][living]
            else:
                fallenProb = 0.5*battleSim(fallen+1, living-1)
                livingProb = 0.5*battleSim(fallen-1, living);
                results[fallen][living] = fallenProb + livingProb
                return results[fallen][living]

This function recursivly caclulates the probabilities and stores the results in an array to be used on the next run.

We now need to test this funciton for a few values before writing a loop to print out all values within a threshold of 0.5 which would be near 50% probability of either team winning. From that we can deduce the trend.

In [3]:
# Test 1
f = 5
l = 5
battleSim(f, l)
print("When the fallen are {} and living are {}, the winrate = {} \n".format(f, l, results[f][l]))

When the fallen are 5 and living are 5, the winrate = 0.1795654296875
In [4]:
for f in range(1,100):
    for l in range(1,100):
        battleSim(f, l)
        print("When the fallen are {} and living are {}, the winrate = {} \n".format(f, l, results[f][l]))
